<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1999, <em>Essays on Galileo and the History
and Philosophy of Science</em>, N. M. Swerdlow and T. H. Levere
(eds.), 3 vols, Toronto: University of Toronto Press.</li>

<li>Duhem, Pierre, 1954, <em>Le Systeme du monde</em>, 6 vols, Paris:
Hermann.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1985, <em>To Save the Phenomena: An Essay
on the Idea of Physical Theory from Plato to Galileo</em>, A. Roger
(trans.), Chicago: University of Chicago Press.</li>

<li>Fantoli, Annibale, 2005, &ldquo;The Disputed Injunction and Its
Role in Galileo&rsquo;s Trial,&rdquo; in E. McMullin (ed.), <em>The
Church and Galileo</em>, Notre Dame, IN: University of Notre Dame
Press, pp. 117&ndash;149.</li>

<li>Feldhay, Rivka, 1995, <em>Galileo and the Church: Political
Inquisition or Critical Dialogue?</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge
University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1998, &ldquo;The Use and Abuse of
Mathematical Entities,&rdquo; in P. Machamer (ed.), <em>The Cambridge
Companion to Galileo</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp.
80&ndash;145.</li>

<li>Feyerabend, Paul, 1975, <em>Against Method</em>, London and New
York: Verso and Humanities Press.</li>

<li>Finocchiaro, Maurice A., 1980, <em>Galileo and the Art of
Reasoning</em>, Dordrecht: D. Reidel.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2005, <em>Retrying Galileo,
1633&ndash;1992</em>, Berkeley: University of California Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2014, <em>The Routledge Guidebook to
Galileo&rsquo;s Dialogue</em>, Abingdon: Routledge.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2019, <em>On Trial for Reason</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Galluzzi, Paolo, 1979, <em>Momento: Studi Galileiani</em>, Rome:
Edizioni dell&rsquo;Ateneo e Bizzarri.</li>

<li>Garber, Daniel, 2010, &ldquo;Philosophia, Historia, Mathematica:
Shifting Sands in the Disciplinary Geography of the Seventeenth
Century,&rdquo; in T. Sorrell, G. A. Rogers, and J. Kraye (eds.),
<em>Scientia in Early Modern Philosophy</em>, Dordrecht: Springer, pp.
1&ndash;17.</li>

<li>Gattei, Stefano, 2019, <em>On the Life of Galileo: Viviani&rsquo;s
Historical Account and Other Early Biographies</em>, Princeton:
Princeton University Press.</li>

<li>Gaukroger, Stephen, 2006, <em>The Emergence of a Scientific
Culture: Science and the Shaping of Modernity, 1210&ndash;1685</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Gendler, Tamar Szab&oacute;, 1998, &ldquo;Galileo and the
Indispensability of Scientific Thought Experiment,&rdquo; <em>British
Journal for the Philosophy of Science</em>, 49 (3):
397&ndash;424.</li>

<li>Geymonat, Ludovico, 1954, <em>Galileo: A Biography and Inquiry
into his Philosophy of Science</em>, S. Drake (trans.), New York:
McGraw Hill.</li>

<li>Giacobbe, Giulio Cesare, 1981, <em>Alle Radici della
Rivoluzione Scientifica Rinascimentale: Le Opere di Pietro Catena sui
Rapporti tra Matematica e Logica</em>, Pisa: Domus Galilaeana.</li>

<li>Giusti, Enrico, 1993, <em>Euclides Reformatus. La Teoria
delle Proporzioni nella Scuola Galileiana</em>, Turin:
Bottati-Boringhieri.</li>

<li>Graney, Christopher M., 2015, <em>Setting Aside All Authority:
Giovanni Battista Riccioli and the Science against Copernicus in the
Age of Galileo</em>, Notre Dame, IN: University of Notre Dame
Press.</li>

<li>Hamou, Philippe, 2021, &ldquo;Instruments and the Senses,&rdquo;
in D. M. Miller and D. Jalobeanu (eds.), <em>The Cambridge History of
Philosophy of the Scientific Revolution</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge
University Press, pp. 331&ndash;349.</li>

<li>Heilbron, John L., 2010, <em>Galileo</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press.</li>

<li>Hooper, Wallace, 1998, &ldquo;Inertial Problems in Galileo&rsquo;s
Preinertial Framework,&rdquo; in P. Machamer (ed.), <em>Cambridge
Companion to Galileo</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, pp.
146&ndash;174.</li>

<li>Jardine, Nicholas, 1976, &ldquo;Galileo&rsquo;s Road to Truth and
the Demonstrative Regress,&rdquo; <em>Studies in History and
Philosophy of Science</em>, 7 (4): 277&ndash;318.</li>

<li>Kepler, Johannes, 1610, <em>Dissertation cum Nuncio Sidereo</em>,
Prague; translated as <em>Kepler&rsquo;s Conversation with
Galileo&rsquo;s Sidereal Messenger</em>, E. Rosen (trans.), New York:
Johnson Reprint Corporation, 1965.</li>

<li>Koertge, Noretta, 1977, &ldquo;Galileo and the Problem of
Accidents.&rdquo; <em>Journal of the History of Ideas</em>, 38 (3):
389&ndash;408.</li>

<li>Koyr&eacute;, Alexandre, 1966, <em>&Eacute;tudes
Galil&eacute;ennes</em>, Paris: Hermann; translated as <em>Galileo
Studies</em>, J. Mepham (trans.), Atlantic Highlands, N.J.: Humanities
Press, 1978.</li>

<li>Lennox, James G., 1986, &ldquo;Aristotle, Galileo and the
&lsquo;Mixed Sciences&rsquo;,&rdquo; in W. A. Wallace (ed.),
<em>Reinterpreting Galileo</em>, Washington, D.C.: Catholic University
of America Press, pp. 29&ndash;52.</li>

<li>Lindberg, David C., and Robert S. Westman (eds.), 1990,
<em>Reappraisals of the Scientific Revolution</em>, Cambridge:
Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Machamer, Peter, 1976, &ldquo;Fictionalism and Realism in 16th
Century Astronomy,&rdquo; in R. S. Westman (ed.), <em>The Copernican
Achievement</em>, Berkeley: University of California Press, pp.
346&ndash;353.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1978, &ldquo;Galileo and the Causes,&rdquo;
in R. Butts and J. C. Pitt (eds.), <em>New Perspectives on
Galileo</em>, Dordrecht: Kluwer, pp. 161&ndash;180.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1991, &ldquo;The Person-Centered Rhetoric
of the Seventeenth Century,&rdquo; in M. Pera and W. R. Shea (eds.),
<em>Persuading Science: The Art of Scientific Rhetoric</em>, Canton,
MA: Science History Publications, pp. 143&ndash;156.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1998a, &ldquo;Galileo&rsquo;s Machines, His
Mathematics, and His Experiments,&rdquo; in P. Machamer (ed.), <em>The
Cambridge Companion to Galileo</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University
Press, pp. 53&ndash;79.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1998b, &ldquo;Introduction,&rdquo; in P.
Machamer (ed.), <em>Cambridge Companion to Galileo</em>, Cambridge:
Cambridge University Press, pp. 1&ndash;26.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1999, &ldquo;Galileo and the Rhetoric of
Relativity,&rdquo; <em>Science and Education</em>, 8 (2):
111&ndash;120; reprinted in E. Gianetto, F. Bevilacqua, and M. R.
Matthews (eds.), 2001, <em>Science Education and Culture: The
Contribution of History and Philosophy of Science</em>, Dordrecht:
Kluwer, pp. 31&ndash;40.</li>

<li>Machamer, Peter, Lindley Darden, and Carl Craver, 2000,
&ldquo;Thinking about Mechanisms,&rdquo; <em>Philosophy of
Science</em>, 67: 1&ndash;25.</li>

<li>Machamer, Peter, and Brian Hepburn, 2004, &ldquo;Galileo and the
Pendulum: Latching on to Time,&rdquo; <em>Science and Education</em>,
13: 333&ndash;347; reprinted in M. R. Matthews, C. F. Gauld, and A.
Stinner (eds.), 2005, <em>The Pendulum: Scientific, Historical,
