<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2005, &ldquo;&lsquo;Spuntar lo scoglio piu
duro&rsquo;: Did Galileo Ever Think the Most Beautiful Thought
Experiment in the History of Science?,&rdquo; <em>Studies in History
and Philosophy of Science Part A</em>, 36 (2): 223&ndash;240.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2008, <em>Reenacting Galileo&rsquo;s
Experiments: Rediscovering the Techniques of Seventeenth-Century
Science</em>, Lewiston, NY: Edwin Mellen Press.</li>

<li>Peterson, Mark A., 2011, <em>Galileo&rsquo;s Muse: Renaissance
Mathematics and the Arts</em>, Cambridge, MA: Harvard University
Press.</li>

<li>Pitt, Joseph C., 1992, <em>Galileo, Human Knowledge, and the Book
of Nature: Method Replaces Metaphysics</em>, Dordrecht: Springer.</li>

<li>Randall, John Herman, 1940, &ldquo;Development of Scientific
Method in the School of Padua,&rdquo; <em>Journal of the History of
Ideas</em>, 1: 177&ndash;206.</li>

<li>Raphael, Renee, 2011, &ldquo;Making Sense of Day 1 of the Two New
Sciences: Galileo&rsquo;s Aristotelian-Inspired Agenda and His Jesuit
